[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'signal goes in one end, a real sentence comes out the other. Let us walk each stage. Stage one, the encoder. A convolutional network reads the raw signal from all 300-plus sensors, and a sequence model guesses the stream of'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'keystrokes, which key in which order. On its own, it is noisy, jittery, and full of mistakes. Stage two, the aligner. Using contrastive learning, it links chunks of brain signal directly to whole'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'words, teaching the model what a word looks like in your neural data, not just one letter at a time. Stage three, a language model. The team fine-tunes an LLM built on QN to take those noisy keystroke guesses, plus the neural word'

